    <item>
      <title>Bush sanctions last-ditch rescue plan for GM and Chrysler</title>
      <link>http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2008/dec/12/automotive-generalmotors</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.15.1/60599?ns=guardian&amp;pageName=Business%3A+Bush+sanctions+last-ditch+rescue+plan+for+General+Motors+and+Chrysler&amp;ch=Business&amp;c3=guardian.co.uk&amp;c4=Automotive+industry+%28Business%29%2CGeneral+Motors%2CFord%2CBusiness%2CUS+news%2CWorld+news%2CUS+economy+%28Business%29&amp;c5=Motoring%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBusiness+Markets%2CUS+Economy&amp;c6=Dan+Milmo&amp;c7=2008_12_12&amp;c8=1133340&amp;c9=article&amp;c10=GU&amp;c11=Business&amp;c12=Automotive+industry&amp;c13=&amp;c14=&amp;h2=GU%2FBusiness%2FAutomotive+industry" width="1" height="1" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;President Bush sanctioned a last-ditch financial rescue of General Motors and Chrysler today after the White House warned that the bankruptcy of either company would deliver a devastating blow to the US economy.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Emergency funding of $14bn (£9bn) is expected to come from the $700bn Troubled Asset Relief Program, which the White House has said was off-limits to the auto industry until its hand was forced by the collapse of bail-out legislation in the Senate on Thursday night. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;GM and Chrysler have hired bankruptcy advisors as the rescue goes to the wire, amid warnings from executives at both companies that their collapse could imperil millions of jobs linked to the industry.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"The current weakened state of the economy is such that it could not withstand a body blow like a disorderly bankruptcy in the auto industry," said Dana Perino, White House press secretary, who added that the TARP fund might be used. A spokeswoman for the US Treasury, which controls the TARP fund, said: "We will stand ready to prevent an imminent failure until Congress reconvenes and acts to address the long-term viability of the industry."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;GM also announced today that it will slash production by a third in the first quarter of next year and temporarily close 21 factories as it scrambles to conserve costs in the worst sales market for 26 years. As result it will make 250,000 fewer vehicles in the first three months of 2009.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;A source close to the situation told Guardian.co.uk that the manufacturers, who could be days away from filing for bankruptcy, were "working very hard with the administration" to secure a compromise. GM indicated in a statement today that the TARP  is its main hope.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"We are encouraged by the White House's willingness to consider other options, including the TARP program, for immediate aid to the domestic auto industry," said GM.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;President Bush and the US treasury secretary, Henry Paulson, have resisted using the $700bn TARP as a funding source for the auto giants, but they blinked today as it became clear that GM and Chrysler had no other outlet. Paulson has $15bn left to allocate in the first $350bn tranche of the fund, which was set up with the explicit mandate of helping troubled banks and financial services companies.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Under one scenario outlined by analysts today, the TARP money could be used as a government guarantee that would underwrite bank loans to the ailing manufacturers.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"The government can ask the banks to make these loans to the industry and pledge that it will guarantee them,. That safeguards the original purpose of the TARP and it is more palatable than giving the money directly," said Aaron Bragman, autos analyst at IHS Global Insight. However, the White House would not give a deadline for striking a bail-out deal.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The New York Stock Exchange opened nervously with the Dow Jones index shedding 1114 points to 8451 by the afternoon – a fall of 1.3%. GM, Chrysler and the third member of the so-called "big three" Detroit-based auto giants, Ford,  employ around 250,000 people directly. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Ford, which is the strongest of the three, has warned that it will be endangered if GM and Chrysler go bust because parts of their shared supply chain will also go under as a result. Fears that a bankruptcy of GM and Chrysler will therefore have a ripple effect through the US economy have been weighing on investors.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;One of the leading Republican opponents of the bail-out package, senator Bob Corker, said he regretted the collapse of the rescue legislation in the Senate on Thursday night. "We were three words away from a deal. That's what kills me," he told CNBC.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Corker said those words were a date for when GM and Chrysler workers would accept wage reductions to bring them in line with rival manufacturers such as Toyota. Republicans had demanded those reductions by next year and accused the United Auto Workers of rejecting that deadline.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Ron Gettelfinger, President of the UAW, said "working for nothing" would not help GM avoid bankruptcy but he admitted that the union would have to make concessions in order to secure a federal bail out. If the White House intervention succeeds it will tide over GM and Chrysler until March 31, who have warned that without the $14bn they will go bankrupt before January. That would leave the drafting of new bail-out legislation to the incoming President Barack Obama and a reconvened Congress and Senate that will have even stronger Democrat representation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Under the terms of the rejected rescue deal, President Bush would have a appointed a "car tsar" to oversee the restructuring of the big three, who are asking for a total of $34bn including the $14bn for GM and Chrysler. The government would have received options to take sizeable equity stakes in the companies in return, as well as imposing tight controls on executive pay.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;However, rebel Republican senators balked at the terms of a bill that was passed by Congress but encountered stiff resistance in the Senate, where Republicans have stronger representation. They demanded  concessions that included the removal of a "jobs bank" that pays wages to temporarily unemployed workers, a sweeping debt restructuring and changes to a UAW health plan. Having reached broad agreement on those principles, the legislation then foundered on the proposed wages reductions. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;However, analysts added that a new bail-out act could be based on the tentative agreement when lawmakers gather in January.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;It was also reported today that GM has hired bankruptcy specialist Harvey Miller of New York-based law firm, Weil Gotshal &amp; Manges in case the White House talks fail. Miller's CV includes dealing with bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers in September.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/automotive"&gt;Automotive industry&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/generalmotors"&gt;General Motors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/ford"&gt;Ford&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa"&gt;United States&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/useconomy"&gt;US economy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk"&gt;guardian.co.uk&lt;/a&gt; &amp;copy; Guardian News &amp; Media Limited 2008 | Use of this content is subject to our &lt;a href="http://users.guardian.co.uk/help/article/0,,933909,00.html"&gt;Terms &amp; Conditions&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/webfeeds/1,,1309488,00.html"&gt;More Feeds&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/DLklHgWlxfbdTtWqVfrhcX2G01c/a"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/DLklHgWlxfbdTtWqVfrhcX2G01c/i" border="0" ismap="true"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
