    <item>
      <title>British ambassador responds to German economic criticism</title>
      <link>http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2008/dec/12/germany-economic-criticisms</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.15.1/27753?ns=guardian&amp;pageName=Politics%3A+British+ambassador+responds+to+German+economic+criticism&amp;ch=Politics&amp;c3=guardian.co.uk&amp;c4=Economic+policy%2CPolitics%2CEuropean+Union+%28News%29%2CGermany%2CUK+news%2CGordon+Brown&amp;c5=Middle+East+Travel%2CCredit+Crunch%2CNot+commercially+useful&amp;c6=Nicholas+Watt+in+Brussels&amp;c7=2008_12_12&amp;c8=1133097&amp;c9=article&amp;c10=GU&amp;c11=Politics&amp;c12=Economic+policy&amp;c13=&amp;c14=&amp;h2=GU%2FPolitics%2FEconomic+policy" width="1" height="1" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Britain has registered its concerns with Berlin after the German finance minister described Gordon Brown's £20bn UK fiscal stimulus plan as "crass Keynesianism".&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Sir Michael Arthur, the British ambassador to Berlin, telephoned the German finance ministry to express Britain's displeasure after Peer Steinbrück intervened in a highly sensitive area of British politics.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The disclosure of the ambassador's intervention came as European Union leaders reached agreement on a Europe-wide €200bn fiscal stimulus plan at their summit in Brussels.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Brown today hailed the deal as a victory against the Tories – and, indirectly, Steinbrück – who have questioned the need for a fiscal stimulus.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"Today's statement is the answer to all the talk of the last few weeks," the prime minister said in Brussels. "Europe is fully united, this is coordinated action."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;His remarks came as the foreign office confirmed that it was so concerned by Steinbrück's attack on the prime minister that the British ambassador had raised the matter with the German finance ministry.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;A spokeswoman for the British embassy in Berlin said: "The ambassador did call the finance ministry. It was to raise a number of issues and to register the fact that we did not agree with Herr Steinbrück. This was not a personal point. It was the politics of it: that we do not agree with his approach and the focus is what is going on in Brussels. Angela Merkel and Gordon Brown are working together."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;David Miliband, the foreign secretary, indicated in Brussels that he was not aware of the ambassador's intervention, showing that Sir Michael's phone call did not amount to a formal diplomatic protest. But Sir Michael's decision showed that Britain was deeply irritated when Steinbrück took aim at one of the main measures Brown has adopted in response to the recession.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The finance minister sparked the row when he tore into Brown's £12.5bn VAT cut – the centrepiece of the government's £20bn fiscal stimulus package – on the grounds that it would saddle Britain with debt that will take years to pay off. He told Newsweek: "The same people who would never touch deficit spending are now tossing around billions. The switch from decades of supply-side politics all the way to a crass Keynesianism is breathtaking.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"When I ask about the origins of the crisis, economists I respect tell me it is the credit-financed growth of recent years and decades. Isn't this the same mistake everyone is suddenly making again, under all the public pressure?"&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The row intensified on Thursday when the budget spokesman for Merkel's CDU party dismissed Brown's main response to Steinbrück – that Britain was caught up in a row between the SPD and the CDU, the two main partners in Germany's "grand coalition" government. Steffen Kampeter said, in a statement released by the Tories: "Peer Steinbrück's comments have nothing whatsoever to do with internal German politics as prime minister Brown has suggested. In questioning the British government's approach, Peer Steinbrück is exactly expressing the views of the German grand coalition."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Brown brushed off the row today and said people should focus on the EU agreement on a Europe-wide fiscal stimulus plan. "This is a fiscal stimulus of 1.5% of our national incomes, around €200bn. It is in line with what will happen in the US and it includes support for judicious reductions in tax. Whatever comments have been made in the last few days – and I have not been privy to the domestic politics of any individual country – this is the answer: that Europe has agreed unanimously to take coordinated action."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Brown hinted that there could be even more measures when the US president elect, Barack Obama, announces a more dramatic US fiscal stimulus package next month. "When next month a new president takes office in America, one who is also committed to fiscal action to cope with the economic slowdown, we will be able to work together and show that Europe and America can make changes that will benefit the economy." &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;He continued: "The economic slowdown is a global problem that requires global action. That is why, in Europe and America, we are united in our belief that governments have a duty to act. We will continue to reject the do-nothing approach. We will not stand by and let the recession take its course. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"What Europe has proved unanimously today is that it is ready to act in a united way to deal with the global downturn and to do so in an ambitious and coordinated manner."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/economy"&gt;Economic policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/eu"&gt;European Union&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/germany"&gt;Germany&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/gordon-brown"&gt;Gordon Brown&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk"&gt;guardian.co.uk&lt;/a&gt; &amp;copy; Guardian News &amp; Media Limited 2008 | Use of this content is subject to our &lt;a href="http://users.guardian.co.uk/help/article/0,,933909,00.html"&gt;Terms &amp; Conditions&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/webfeeds/1,,1309488,00.html"&gt;More Feeds&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/7Y8G4hb2MHHCXt2O02D_KM6KRqk/a"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/7Y8G4hb2MHHCXt2O02D_KM6KRqk/i" border="0" ismap="true"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      <category domain="http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk">UK news</category>
      <category domain="http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics">Economic policy</category>
      <category domain="http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics">Politics</category>
      <category domain="http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics">Gordon Brown</category>
      <category domain="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world">European Union</category>
      <category domain="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world">Germany</category>
      <pubDate>Fri, 12 Dec 2008 10:28:13 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2008/dec/12/germany-economic-criticisms</guid>
      <dc:creator>Nicholas Watt in Brussels</dc:creator>
