    <item>
      <title>UK blocking European Congo force</title>
      <link>http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2008/dec/12/congo-european-union-foreign-policy</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.15.1/26307?ns=guardian&amp;pageName=World+news%3A+UK+blocking+European+Congo+force&amp;ch=World+news&amp;c3=The+Guardian&amp;c4=Congo+%28News%29%2CForeign+policy%2CEuropean+Union+%28News%29%2CUnited+Nations+%28News%29%2CDavid+Miliband%2CMilitary+UK%2CPolitics%2CWorld+news%2CUK+news%2CAid+and+development+%28Society%29%2CSociety&amp;c5=Society+Weekly%2CMiddle+East+Travel%2CPolicy+Society%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CCharities&amp;c6=Ian+Traynor%2CJulian+Borger&amp;c7=2008_12_12&amp;c8=1132883&amp;c9=article&amp;c10=GU&amp;c11=World+news&amp;c12=Democratic+Republic+of+the+Congo&amp;c13=&amp;c14=&amp;h2=GU%2FWorld+news%2FDemocratic+Republic+of+the+Congo" width="1" height="1" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Britain is refusing to take part in a proposed European armed intervention in eastern Congo despite a growing clamour for an EU force to help avoid a bigger humanitarian disaster.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;At a summit of European leaders in Brussels last night, foreign ministers from the 27 countries discussed proposals to dispatch a force of up to 1,500 to North Kivu in eastern Congo.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;While Ban Ki-moon, the UN secretary general, Javier Solana, the EU foreign policy chief, several ministers and human rights groups pushed for a robust  intervention under European command, David Miliband, the foreign secretary, argued any action should be taken through the UN and its 17,000-strong Monuc (UN organisation mission) peacekeeping contingent.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Solana tabled a menu of four military options for the EU, the first of which would entail the deployment of a British or German battle group of around 1,500 troops to Goma and North Kivu.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The British view such an option as being out of the question, and despite Miliband having spearheaded a peace mission to Congo last month, the government has strong reservations about giving a green light to any European mission.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;One European diplomat told the Guardian: "Miliband is adamant that the EU should not get involved. Britain and Germany are leading the resistance. But something has to be done."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Monuc force in Congo is to be increased by 3,000, but it will take months for the reinforcements to arrive. Amid reports of massacre, atrocities, and mass rape from the region, Human Rights Watch - which provided testimony of the massacre of 150 civilians in the North Kivu town of Kiwanja last month - urged the EU to take action.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"The European Union should not wait for further killings to act. The current UN forces simply don't have the capacity or numbers to protect," it said.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Last night Lord Malloch Brown, the Foreign Office minister for Africa, Asia and the United Nations, said: "Clearly we have felt the optimal solution was strengthening and transforming Monuc into something more able to do the job. The fact is we're not getting Monuc enlarged in the timeline hoped for."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;He said that if other European states wanted to contribute to Monuc or send troops to Congo alongside the UN mission, "then more power to them ... We are absolutely not going to be an obstruction." &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;EU ministers also discussed an updated European security concept presented by Solana giving priority to the fight against terrorism - while Brussels counter-terrorist units were arresting 14 people suspected of links with al-Qaida.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Belgian prosecutors said one of those detained might have been planning a suicide attack and did not rule out that the summit of 27 government leaders itself could have been a target.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Solana's proposals last night for four different EU military missions to Congo followed a plea for help to Brussels from the UN secretary-general. Ban has asked the EU to command an armed mission for a minimum of four months to secure supplies for 250,000 displaced people in North Kivu and to protect civilians.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"This would allow us to stabilise the fragile security environment and avert a humanitarian catastrophe," Ban wrote to Solana. He said the EU force should secure Goma airport and other strategic buildings, major population centres in North Kivu, and supply routes around Goma.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;"The rapid deployment of such a force would constitute a powerful political message that the entire international community is determined not to allow a further deterioration."&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Like the UK, Germany opposes sending its battle group, which is also on standby for deployment. Bernard Kouchner, the French foreign minister and an apostle of armed humanitarian intervention, is keen for the EU to act, but diplomats are unsure if he has the backing of Nicolas Sarkozy.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/congo"&gt;Democratic Republic of the Congo&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/foreignpolicy"&gt;Foreign policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/eu"&gt;European Union&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/unitednations"&gt;United Nations&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/davidmiliband"&gt;David Miliband&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/military"&gt;Military&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/internationalaidanddevelopment"&gt;International aid and development&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk"&gt;guardian.co.uk&lt;/a&gt; &amp;copy; Guardian News &amp; Media Limited 2008 | Use of this content is subject to our &lt;a href="http://users.guardian.co.uk/help/article/0,,933909,00.html"&gt;Terms &amp; Conditions&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/webfeeds/1,,1309488,00.html"&gt;More Feeds&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/PJizwwk2SKAgMYYhX12YqcN9T6U/a"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/PJizwwk2SKAgMYYhX12YqcN9T6U/i" border="0" ismap="true"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
