      <title>Big bill, bad meal: Hélène Darroze at the Connaught</title>
      <link>http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/wordofmouth/2008/dec/12/foodanddrink-restaurants</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.15.1/19681?ns=guardian&amp;pageName=Life+and+style%3A+Big+bill%2C+bad+meal%3A+H%C3%A9l%C3%A8ne+Darroze+at+the+Connaught&amp;ch=Life+and+style&amp;c3=guardian.co.uk&amp;c4=Food+and+drink+%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style%2CRestaurants+%28Life+and+style%29&amp;c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CFood+and+Drink&amp;c6=Jay+Rayner&amp;c7=2008_12_12&amp;c8=1133004&amp;c9=article&amp;c10=GU&amp;c11=Life+and+style&amp;c12=blog&amp;c13=&amp;c14=Word+of+Mouth+blog&amp;h2=GU%2FLife+and+style%2Fblog%2FWord+of+Mouth+blog" width="1" height="1" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;What price dinner? Or, to put it another way, what price your dinner? How much are you prepared to pay to eat out? It's a pointed question particularly at a time like this, when money, as the sainted Mr Hucknall once said, is too tight to mention. At the end of last week's restaurant review I told you to look out for this week's review, because the bill would make your eyes bulge.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Well here it is, my &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2008/dec/14/jay-rayner-helene-darroze-the-connaught"&gt;review of Hélène Darroze at the Connaught&lt;/a&gt; where dinner in the evening will cost you £275 for two, as long as you don't get too ambitious on the wine list. From long experience in this game I know this will drive some people nuts. Funnily enough I suspect the only thing that will make this review acceptable in some people's eyes is that I disliked the food so very much. It's a bad review of a restaurant that costs £275 for two. If it had been a good review of a restaurant that costs £275 for two that would be regarded as truly despicable. Which I think is a little odd.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There are some people – hell, a lot of people – who think spending significant sums of money on restaurant experiences is just plain wrong. I tackled this issue in my book, the Man who Ate The World and I'm not sure I can improve on what I said then:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;There is one reason for this and one reason only: we need food to survive. Therefore it is a necessity and to crash the plastic until it smoulders on a necessity is regarded somehow as wrong. Which is to completely misunderstand the point of restaurants and high-end gastronomy. Nobody goes to restaurants for nutritional reasons. Nobody eats hot smoked foie gras with caramelised onion purée to stave off rickets. They go for experiences, and what price a really top experience? &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Let's put it another way. How much would you be willing to pay to see your football team play in the FA cup final? £100 a ticket? £200 a ticket? £500 for a really good seat? You wouldn't think twice about it. A place in the front row for Robert de Niro on the stage?  A few hundred quid, easy. The chance to see Sinatra in his prime? Hell, you name the price. And what does that money buy you? Nothing but memories, and the right to say you were there. Serious gastronomy is no different.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In this case £275 of The Observer's money brought me memories of the wrong kind. That awful dish of sweetbreads roasted in astringent tandoori spices gives me nightmares. But I have had big ticket dinners paid for – whisper it – with my own money, which I thought worth every single penny. I treasure those memories.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So am I wrong? Is it simply impossible for a restaurant experience to be worth these sorts of sums? Which means I'm asking you whether you think I am deluded (form an orderly queue please). Or do we need to re-categorise them alongside once-in-a-lifetime Sinatra/De Niro experiences? Let the shouting begin.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/foodanddrink"&gt;Food &amp; drink&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/restaurants"&gt;Restaurants&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk"&gt;guardian.co.uk&lt;/a&gt; &amp;copy; Guardian News &amp; Media Limited 2008 | Use of this content is subject to our &lt;a href="http://users.guardian.co.uk/help/article/0,,933909,00.html"&gt;Terms &amp; Conditions&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/webfeeds/1,,1309488,00.html"&gt;More Feeds&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/Tl6uYggDtDa7m8OdUVcEE2tYcYI/a"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/Tl6uYggDtDa7m8OdUVcEE2tYcYI/i" border="0" ismap="true"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
