    <item>
      <title>Where are all the environmental online videos?</title>
      <link>http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/ethicallivingblog/2008/dec/12/climate-change-youtube-videos</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.15.1/58578?ns=guardian&amp;pageName=Environment%3A+Watch+this%2C+or+the+planet+gets+it%21&amp;ch=Environment&amp;c3=guardian.co.uk&amp;c4=Environment%2CActivists+%28Environment%29%2CClimate+change+%28Environment%29&amp;c5=Climate+Change%2CEthical+Living&amp;c6=Leo+Hickman&amp;c7=2008_12_12&amp;c8=1133102&amp;c9=article&amp;c10=GU&amp;c11=Environment&amp;c12=Activists&amp;c13=&amp;c14=&amp;h2=GU%2FEnvironment%2FActivists" width="1" height="1" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;When was the last time a &lt;a href="http://www.youtube.com/"&gt;YouTube&lt;/a&gt; video focused on an environment issue went truly viral?  Probably about a year ago when &lt;a href="http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/education/2004083774_terrifyingvideo20m.html"&gt;Greg Craven&lt;/a&gt;'s nine-minute lecture entitled "&lt;a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zORv8wwiadQ&amp;feature=channel"&gt;The Most Terrifying Video You'll Ever See&lt;/a&gt;" wracked up several millions views.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;But such examples are pretty rare amid all the music videos, krazy dance routines and funny animal clips that usually hog YouTube's Most Viewed charts.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;An accurate reflection of what grabs the attention of the internet generation? Yes, but it does seem a little odd that amid all the &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2008/dec/09/climate-change-science-environment"&gt;current talk&lt;/a&gt; on how best to engage a largely apathetic public about our multitude of environmental problems then more people haven't tried to come up with other Craven-esque methods of spreading the message. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Asking people to read their way their the &lt;a href="http://www.ipcc.ch/"&gt;IPCC&lt;/a&gt; reports doesn't seem to be doing the trick, that's for sure.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Animation seems to be a popular technique for creating environmental videos online. &lt;a href="http://www.planestupid.com/"&gt;Plane Stupid&lt;/a&gt;'s Leo Murray recently created &lt;a href="http://www.vimeo.com/1709110?pg=embed&amp;sec=1709110"&gt;this video&lt;/a&gt; as part of his MA in animation at the Royal College of Art, but it has yet to go viral beyond environmental circles.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;There's a multitude of other environmental animations on the net, but none seem to have broken out and become a mainstream hit.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;MTV-style videos that are light on the message and high on style seem to be another technique that has had some success. For example, the &lt;a href="http://www.blueman.com/"&gt;Blue Man Group&lt;/a&gt; produced this &lt;a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QM-mfEMssy8"&gt;short video&lt;/a&gt; about global warming a couple of years ago and it has achieved more than two million views to date.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This video called &lt;a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7FVZSUsT-Ws"&gt;Global Warming: A Point of No Return&lt;/a&gt; has had more than 300,000 views, but it's not my cup of tea at all. I think in our cynical times over-emoting like this risks putting more people off than winning them over. Also, the music, especially in the second half, is truly awful.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So, what have you seen out there that should be seen by others? And, more importantly, can YouTube-style videos ever be an effective medium for stoking passion about these issues?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/activists"&gt;Activists&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/climatechange"&gt;Climate change&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk"&gt;guardian.co.uk&lt;/a&gt; &amp;copy; Guardian News &amp; Media Limited 2008 | Use of this content is subject to our &lt;a href="http://users.guardian.co.uk/help/article/0,,933909,00.html"&gt;Terms &amp; Conditions&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/webfeeds/1,,1309488,00.html"&gt;More Feeds&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/zjsNq8_RLq8QLz07uhbMrs93HM0/a"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feedads.googleadservices.com/~at/zjsNq8_RLq8QLz07uhbMrs93HM0/i" border="0" ismap="true"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
